text.tspan: 1. Email Subject and Content1.1. Subject - If this relates to a vessel, please start with the vessels’ full name followed by the subject matter.Please do not use vessel name abbreviations. If not the subject should contain the entity it relates to (e.g.Executive Offshore) and followed by the subject matter.1.2. For emails that are forwarded and or replied and the relevance of the email has changed, please ensurethe subject is updated in line with what the text relates to. When the subject builds up to a lot of “FW”(forward) prior the email subject, please remove these “FW”s.1.3. When communicating with an external party, please do not give internal instructions to colleagues – thisgives an impression of poor teamwork. The email sent to external parties can be forwarded internally to therelevant person with instructions.1.4. Do not forward internal messages to external parties. Drafting a new message with the same text isalways more professional and ensures that unwanted or sensitive information is not relayed to the externalparty by oversight.1.5. Email is a formal means of communication and has the same importance and relevance as earlier letters.Hence draft your mails properly with correct syntax and check for spelling mistakes before sending. The mailbody should be kept brief and to the point. Brake long paragraphs into small logical paragraphs so that it iseasy for the reader.1.6. When sending email to vessels, please consolidate emails from one department on one subject andsend it together to avoid flooding vessels inbox. Avoid keeping the vessel in copy of all message to agents. 1.7. Avoid sending emails with “High Importance” unless it requires an immediate reply.2. Addressing the mails2.1. When sending out emails, please copy the group email id you are part of and any other relevant group.E.g. if you are HSEQA Department and it is a crew related matter, address “to” the person / vessel concernedwith 2.2. Avoid sending messages to more than one person in “TO” field. If it is unavoidable then it is assumed toapply identically to all of the persons in the “TO” field. If there is a separate message to convey to eachindividual, this must be broken down individually within the same email.2.3. If a mail is addressed to you in the “TO” field, you are expected to respond promptly.2.4. If a mail is addressed to you in the “CC” field, it is assumed that you have received the email and areaware of the contents of the email.2.5. Please avoid the habit of “reply all” - remove unnecessary recipients prior replying. As a rule, avoidcopying too many groups and persons to avoid unnecessary flooding of emails.11OCCUPATIONAL HEALTH AND SAFETY11.1OFFICE WORK ENVIRONMENT- ASSESSMENT OF OH&S ASPECTS AT WORK STATIONSFollowing hazards pertaining to various activities conducted at company’s shore work stations are assessed and highlighted:1)Compactus units for moving file cabinets: These activities present mechanical hazards and may result in injuries. Ensure thatno person is inside before moving the compactus.2)Office Activities: Routine office activities may present certain health hazards to employees and visitors. The hazard is particularlyserious with respect to spread of certain contagious / infectious diseases at work place due to interaction / sharing of food etc. In thisregard following company policies shall be strictly implemented:No exotic plants or uncooked animal product should be brought in to the company’s premises.All staff shall cover their nose and mouth when sneezing or coughing and wash hands with soap and water afterwards.Maintain good personal and environmental hygiene.If any staff develops influenza like symptoms such as fever, sore throat and cough they should, consult their doctor promptly, wear a surgical mask and takerest at home.11.2HOUSEKEEPINGEffective housekeeping can eliminate some workplace hazards and help get a job done safely and properly. Poor housekeeping canfrequently contribute to accidents by hiding hazards that cause injuries. If the sight of paper, debris, clutter and spills is accepted asnormal, then other more serious health and safety hazards may be taken for granted.Housekeeping is not just cleanliness. It includes keeping work areas neat and orderly; maintaining halls and floors free of slip and triphazards; and removing of waste materials (e.g., paper, cardboard) and other fire hazards from work areas. It also requires payingattention to important details such as the layout of the whole workplace, the adequacy of storage facilities, and maintenance. Goodhousekeeping is also a basic part of accident and fire prevention.Effective housekeeping is an ongoing operation: It is not a hit-and-miss cleanup done occasionally. Periodic “panic” cleanups arecostly and ineffective in reducing accidents.Poor housekeeping can be a cause of accidents, such as:Tripping over loose objects on floors, stairs and platformsBeing hit by falling objectsSlipping on greasy, wet or dirty surfaces
